            <table border="1", cellpadding="10", cellspacing="10">
                <tr style="font-size: 50px;">
                    <th colspan="3", id="top"><em>Noli Me Tangere</em> Characters</th>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><img src="https://i.pinimg.com/564x/4b/d6/37/4bd637cb3bde69356fc77bedb8b160b2.jpg" height="200" width="200"></td>
                    <td style="font-size: 30px;">Juan Crisóstomo Ibarra y Magsalin</td>
                    <td style="font-size: 20px;">
                        <ul>
                            <li>He is the novel's protagonist and is portrayed as a young, educated Filipino who has returned to the Philippines after studying in Europe.</li>
                            <li>Crisostomo Ibarra is a symbol of hope for reform and represents the educated Filipino class during the Spanish colonial period.</li>
                            <li>The novel explores the social and political issues of the time, and Ibarra's character is central to the story's themes of nationalism, social injustice, and the desire for change.</li>
                        </ul>
                    </td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><img src="https://i.pinimg.com/564x/d4/97/3b/d4973b272e99273233855e15488d4849.jpg" height="200" width="200"></td>
                    <td style="font-size: 30px;">María Clara de los Santos y Alba</td>
                    <td style="font-size: 20px;">
                        <ul>
                            <li>Her character embodies the idealized image of a woman during the Spanish colonial period in the Philippines.</li>
                            <li>She is known for her grace, modesty, and her skills in various feminine pursuits such as embroidery and music.</li>
                            <li>The character of Maria Clara has become an iconic figure in Philippine literature and culture.</li>
                        </ul>
                    </td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><img src="https://static.wikia.nocookie.net/mariaclaraatibarra/images/8/83/Padre_Damaso_character_image.png/revision/latest/scale-to-width-down/1000?cb=20230125012508" height="200" width="200"></td>
                    <td style="font-size: 30px;">Padre Dámaso Verdolagas</td>
                    <td style="font-size: 20px;">
                        <ul>
                            <li>He is one of the most prominent and antagonistic figures in the novel.</li>
                            <li>Padre Damaso is a Spanish friar who serves as the parish priest in the town where the story takes place.</li>
                            <li>Padre Damaso is portrayed as a corrupt and abusive character, using his position to exploit the local population, particularly the Filipinos.</li>
                        </ul>
                    </td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><img src="https://i.pinimg.com/564x/72/db/d0/72dbd0d41758807123ad4bc917e6a5c7.jpg" height="200" width="200"></td>
                    <td style="font-size: 30px;">Padre Salvi</td>
                    <td style="font-size: 20px;">
                        <ul>
                            <li>He is a Spanish Franciscan friar who serves as the curate of San Diego, the town where the story is set.</li>
                            <li>Unlike Padre Damaso, Padre Salvi is portrayed as a more moderate and less openly abusive friar, but he is still a symbol of the Spanish friars' influence and presence in the Philippines during the Spanish colonial era.</li>
                            <li>Padre Salvi's character plays a significant role in the narrative, and his interactions with other characters contribute to the development of the novel's themes of colonial oppression, religious hypocrisy, and social injustice.</li>
                        </ul>
                    </td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><img src="https://static.wikia.nocookie.net/mariaclaraatibarra/images/4/4a/Kapitan_Tiago_character_image.png/revision/latest?cb=20230121080402" height="200" width="200"></td>
                    <td style="font-size: 30px;">Kapitan Tiago</td>
                    <td style="font-size: 20px;">
                        <ul>
                            <li>He is an affluent Filipino who is a friend of Crisostomo Ibarra.</li>
                            <li>Kapitan Tiago is often depicted as a well-meaning and generous character who uses his wealth to support various charitable causes and events in the community.</li>
                            <li>His character represents the ilustrado class in the Philippines during the Spanish colonial period.</li>
                            <li>Kapitan Tiago's character is important in the novel because he illustrates the tension and complexities faced by the Filipino elite during that period.</li>
                        </ul>
                    </td>
                </tr>
